<subSubSection id="F3D4780279841A7C9EFC1E06069A0977" pageId="0" pageNumber="155" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="B819E689FD35016F955446A7B5E0DDD7" pageId="0" pageNumber="155">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0E2240A831AA5B9AEE457666B9EAD7B5" pageId="0" pageNumber="155">
At the background of the white flowers, two red glands at the top of staminodes are an important indicator for the pollinators to visit the plants. It is obvious that nectars are hidden at the back of the indicator (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="AEF19905362388C26A3D2B4053EC0BAF" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Flower morphology of Allocheilos rubroglandulosus W. H. Chen &amp; Y. M. Shui, sp. nov. (From holotype, photographed by S. W. Guo and Y. M. Shui) A inflorescence B right part of the inflorescence C left part of the inflorescence D lateral view of the leaf part of the inflorescence E face view of the flower F face view indicating 3 staminodes, middle white and lateral 2 red on the top G lateral view of flower indicating stamens H opened corolla indicating the stamens and staminodes and the swollen nodes at the base of filaments. Notes: at anther, br bract; cx calyx lobe, dc disc, fm filament, gl glandular, sd staminode, sl style, sm stigma, sn swollen nodes at base of filament." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.157.32729.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/445932" pageId="0" pageNumber="155">5C</figureCitation>
).The discovery will provide us an opportunity to explore the diversity and evolution of staminodes of the genus in 
<taxonomicName id="674182634B653D1DCC9530BBFD656CC0" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Thalictrum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Ranunculales" pageId="0" pageNumber="155" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Gesneriaceae</taxonomicName>
and the other groups endemic to the karst regions in China and the adjacent countries (Laos, Myanmar, Thailand and Vietnam).
</paragraph>
